Introduction¶

This notebook presents multiple bandit algorithms. In multi-armed bandits, at each time step agent has to choose between $k$ different actions. Each action is associated with immediate stochastic reward. For simplicity we assume reward is drawn from normal distribution. Each arm has different mean reward, which is hidden from the agent.

The main point of bandit algorithms is to balance exploitation with exploration, such that to maximise cumulative reward over certain number of time steps. We also use a concept of regret, which is difference between perfect play (always choosing arm with highest mean reward) and agent actual play.

Contents

  • Explore Then Commit
  • Epsilon Greedy
  • Upper Confidence Bound (UCB)
  • Predictor UCB (PUCB) - as per AlphaZero paper
  • Conclusion - compare algorithms

References

  • Reinforcement Learning: An Introduction - UCB algorithm, good explanation, see chapter 2.7
  • Mastering the game of Go without human knowledge - modified PUCB algorithm, see appendix
  • Bandit Algorithms - rigorous math treatment, check book and blog posts series

import numpy as np

Environment

In [2]:
class BanditEnv:
    def __init__(self):
        """Multi-armed bandit with 10-arms
        
        See Also: RL: An Introduction, Sutton and Barto, 2018, chapter 2.3
        """
        self.size = 10                                       # 10 arms
        self.means = np.array([0.25, -0.75, 1.5, 0.5, 1.25,  # eyeball fig 2.1
                               -1.5, -0.25, -1, 0.75, -0.5])
    def step(self, action):
        assert action == int(action)
        assert 0 <= action < self.size
        
        reward = np.random.normal(loc=self.means[action])     # float
        return reward

Helpers¶

In [3]:
def argmax_rand(arr):
    """Pick max value, break ties randomly."""
    assert isinstance(arr, np.ndarray)
    assert len(arr.shape) == 1
    
    # break ties randomly, np.argmax() always picks first max
    return np.random.choice(np.flatnonzero(arr == arr.max()))

Cumulative regret

In [4]:
def cumulative_regret(rewards, max_reward):
    """Calculate cumulative regret for past time steps."""
    assert isinstance(rewards, np.ndarray)
    assert len(rewards.shape) == 1
    assert max_reward == float(max_reward)
    
    regrets = max_reward - rewards
    return np.cumsum(regrets)

def plot_arm_estimated_values(env, Q):
    assert env.size == int(env.size)
    assert isinstance(env.means, np.ndarray)
    assert len(env.means.shape) == 1
    assert isinstance(Q, np.ndarray)
    assert len(Q.shape) == 1
    assert len(env.means) == len(Q)
    
    plt.scatter(range(env.size), env.means, color='blue', marker='o', label='true')
    plt.scatter(range(env.size), Q, color='red', marker='x', label='estim.')
    plt.legend()
    plt.title('True and Estimated Values')
    plt.ylabel('Arm Value')
    plt.xlabel('Arm Number')
    plt.show()

    assert len(cum_regrets.shape) == 1

In [7]:
def plot_experiments(data, label, color, axes=None):
    """
    Params:
        data (np.ndarray): experiment results, shape: [nb_exp, len_exp]
        color (str or tuple): matplotlib compatible color definition
        axes (tuple of two np.)
    """
    assert isinstance(data, np.ndarray)
    assert len(data.shape) == 2
    assert axes is None or len(axes) == 2
    
    if axes is None:
        _, (ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(nrows=1, ncols=2, figsize=(16,6))
    else:
        ax1, ax2 = axes

    x = range(data.shape[1])
    means = data.mean(axis=0)
    stds = data.std(axis=0)

    #ax1.plot([0], [0], c=color, alpha=0.0, label=label)
    ax1.plot(x, data.T, c=color, alpha=0.1)
    ax1.set_title('Cumulative Regret - Individual Runs')
    ax1.set_xlabel('Time Step')
    ax1.set_ylabel('Regret')

    #ax2.plot([0], [0], c=color, alpha=0.0, label=label)
    ax2.plot(x, means, c=color, label=label)
    ax2.fill_between(x, means-stds, means+stds, color=color, alpha=0.1)
    ax2.set_title('Cumulative Regret - Mean and Standard Deviation')
    ax2.set_xlabel('Time Step')
    ax2.set_ylabel('Regret')
    ax2.legend()

    if axes is None:
        plt.tight_layout()
        plt.show()
    
    return axes

def run_experiment(num_runs, algorithm, **kwargs):
    """Run multiple experiments and return cumulative regrets."""
    assert num_runs == int(num_runs)
    experiment_results = []  # cumulative regrets, shape [num_runs, np_total]
    for _ in range(num_runs):
        Q, rewards = algorithm(**kwargs)
        experiment_results.append(cumulative_regret(rewards, env.means.max()))
    return np.array(experiment_results)

Explore Then Commit¶

The simplest way to solve bandits, first explore all arms equally for preset number of time steps, then commit to the arm with highest average reward.

  • if exploration phase is too short, then there is a risk we don't learn enough to select correct arm and we may commit to sub-optimal choice
  • if exploration phase is too long, then we keep selecting poor arms for no good reason

For good explanation see First steps: Explore-then-Commit blog post by author of Bandit Algorithms book.

In [10]:
def explore_then_commit(env, nb_total, nb_explore):
    """Explore for nb_explore time stepsn, then commit to one arm.
    
    Params:
        env (BanditEnv): environment to solve
        nb_total (int): how many time steps in total
        nb_explore (int): of total steps, how many use for exploration
    
    Returns:
        Q (np.ndarray): array with value estimates, shape: [nb_arms]
        rewards (np.ndarray): history of rewards, shape: [nb_total]
    """
    assert isinstance(env, BanditEnv)
    assert nb_total == int(nb_total) and nb_total > 0
    assert nb_explore == int(nb_explore) and nb_explore <= nb_total
    
    rewards = []              # rewards for each time step, shape: [nb_total]
    
    assert nb_explore % env.size == 0
    
    Q = np.zeros(env.size)    # average reward for each arm, shape: [n_arms]
    N = np.zeros(env.size)    # num times each arm pulled,   shape: [n_arms]
    
    for k in range(nb_total):
        if k <= nb_explore:                  # <- exploration phase
            A = k % env.size                 # pick actions in order
            R = env.step(A)
            N[A] += 1                        # num visits
            Q[A] += (1/N[A]) * (R - Q[A])    # incremental mean
            
        else:                                # <- commitment phase
            A = argmax_rand(Q)
            R = env.step(A)
        
        rewards.append(R)
    
    return Q, np.array(rewards)

Epsilon Greedy¶

In epsilon greedy algorithm, we pick best arm with probability $ P = 1 - \epsilon $ and explore random arm with $ P = \epsilon $

In [16]:
def epsilon_greedy(env, nb_total, eps, eps_factor=1.0):
    """Choose best with P = 1-eps, explore randomly with P = eps.
    
    Params:
        env (BanditEnv): environment to solve
        nb_total (int): how many time steps in total
        eps (float): exploration fraction, range: [0..1]
        eps_factor (float): epsilon decay, range: [0..1]
    
    Returns:
        Q (np.ndarray): array with value estimates, shape: [nb_arms]
        rewards (np.ndarray): history of rewards, shape: [nb_total]
    """
    assert isinstance(env, BanditEnv)
    assert nb_total == int(nb_total)
    assert eps == float(eps) and 0 <= eps <= 1
    assert eps_factor == float(eps_factor) and 0 <= eps_factor <= 1
    
    rewards = []
    
    Q = np.zeros(env.size)   # average reward for each arm, shape: [n_arms]
    N = np.zeros(env.size)   # num times each arm pulled,   shape: [n_arms]
    
    for _ in range(nb_total):
        if np.random.rand() > eps:
            A = argmax_rand(Q)               # pick best known arm
        else:
            A = np.random.randint(env.size)  # explore randomly
        R = env.step(A)
        N[A] += 1
        Q[A] += (1/N[A]) * (R - Q[A])        # incremental mean
        
        eps *= eps_factor                    # epsilon decay
        rewards.append(R)
        
    return Q, np.array(rewards)

Upper Confidence Bound¶

Upper Confidence Bound is a clever algorithm which balances exploration and exploitation. It is proven to be optimal way of solving bandit problems, see Bandit Algorithm book for mathematical treatment. Node score can be calculated as follows

$$ \frac{v_i}{n_i} + c \sqrt{\frac{\log N}{n_i}} $$
  • $v_i$ is total reward for arm $i$
  • $n_i$ is number of visits for arm $i$
  • $c$ is exploration constant, usually set to $\sqrt 2$
  • $N$ is a total number of time steps so far
  • $n_i$ is number of visits to arm $i$

For in depth explanation see: Reinforcement Learning: An Introduction by Sutton and Barto

In [21]:
def upper_confidence_bound(env, nb_total, c_param):
    """Actively balance exploration/exploitation using Clever Math
    
    Params:
        env (BanditEnv): environment to solve
        nb_total (int): how many time steps in total
        c_param (float): exploration param, higher means explore more
        
    Returns:
        Q (np.ndarray): array with value estimates, shape: [nb_arms]
        rewards (np.ndarray): history of rewards, shape: [nb_total]
    """
    assert isinstance(env, BanditEnv)
    assert nb_total == int(nb_total)
    assert c_param == float(c_param) and c_param >= 0
    
    rewards = []
    
    V = np.zeros(env.size)   # sum of reward for each arm, shape: [n_arms]
    N = np.zeros(env.size)   # num times each arm pulled,   shape: [n_arms]
    
    for k in range(nb_total):
        
        if k < env.size:     # visit each arm at least once
            A = k
        else:                # the famous UCB formula in vectorised form
            scores = V / N + c_param * np.sqrt( np.log(N.sum()) / N )
            A = argmax_rand(scores)
        
        R = env.step(A)
        N[A] += 1
        V[A] += R

        rewards.append(R)
        
    Q = V / N                # calculate arm values before returning
    return Q, np.array(rewards)

Solve the environment. Note that top nodes are very tightly approximated, while poorest nodes are only vaguely approximated. This is because UCB actively focuses on best nodes early (but keeps exploring a bit).

In [22]:

Predictor UCB¶

PUCB is a modification to UCB which allows for injecting priors. Algorithm here is implementation from AlphaZero.

For original paper see Multi-armed Bandits with Episode Context by Christopher D. Rosin

For full description see Mastering the game of Go without human knowledge by Silver et al., methods appendix.

The formula is as follows

$$ \frac{v_i}{n_i} + c_{\text{puct}} P(a) \frac{\sqrt{N}}{1 + n_i} $$
In [26]:
def predictor_UCB(env, nb_total, c_param, priors):
    """Similar to UCB, but allows injecting priors.
    
    Params:
        env (BanditEnv): environment to solve
        nb_total (int): how many time steps in total
        c_param (float): exploration param, higher means explore more
        priors (np.ndarray): prior probability distribution, must sum to 1
        
    Returns:
        Q (np.ndarray): array with value estimates, shape: [nb_arms]
        rewards (np.ndarray): history of rewards, shape: [nb_total]
    """
    assert isinstance(env, BanditEnv)
    assert nb_total == int(nb_total)
    assert c_param == float(c_param) and c_param >= 0
    assert isinstance(priors, np.ndarray)
    assert len(priors.shape) == 1
    assert abs(priors.sum() - 1) < 1e-6
    
    rewards = []
    
    V = np.zeros(env.size)
    N = np.zeros(env.size)
    Q = np.zeros(env.size)
    
    for k in range(nb_total):
        
        scores = Q + c_param * priors * np.sqrt(N.sum())/(1+N)
        A = argmax_rand(scores)
        
        R = env.step(A)
        
        N[A] += 1
        V[A] += R
        Q[A] = V[A] / N[A]
        
        rewards.append(R)
    
    return Q, np.array(rewards)

Helper softmax function

In [27]:
# see e.g. here: https://deepnotes.io/softmax-crossentropy
def softmax(x):
    """Numerically stable softmax"""
    max_ = np.max(x, axis=-1, keepdims=True)       # shape: (n_batch, 1)
    ex = np.exp(x - max_)                          # shape: (n_batch, n_out)
    ex_sum = np.sum(ex, axis=-1, keepdims=True)    # shape: (n_batch, 1)
    return ex / ex_sum                             # shape: (n_batch, n_out)

Prepare some more priors for experiments. Note that in one case we use bad priors which are essentially incorrect. Because exploration weight decreases as number of time steps increase, even with poor priors PUCB still converges to correct solution.

In [31]:
priorsG = softmax(env.means)           # good priors based on true values
priorsM = softmax([1]*len(env.means))  # equal .1 prior for all arm
priorsB = softmax(-env.means)          # bad priors, based on inverse of true values
